<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="496" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,509,858]" pageId="1" pageNumber="496">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,321,653,678]" pageId="1" pageNumber="496">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[328,496,653,677]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Dexoris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="496" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="chome" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[328,496,653,677]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="496">Dexoris chome</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[503,592,653,678]" pageId="1" pageNumber="496" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[503,592,653,678]" pageId="1" pageNumber="496">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
is the only species in the genus with a brachelytrous male. The only known male of the new species differs from other fully winged 
<taxonomicName box="[786,875,690,713]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Dexoris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="496" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[786,875,690,713]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="496">Dexoris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
males in having shorter elytra, nonfunctional and vestigial hind wings, short robust antennae and the pronotum widest in the anterior third (
<figureCitation box="[1163,1229,725,750]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 8" captionStartId="1.[151,264,1675,1698]" captionTargetBox="[153,1432,912,1650]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[151,1436,910,1654]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 8. Dexoris chome sp. nov. 1 general appearance, 2 hind wing, 3 maxillae and labium, 4 mandible, 5 labrum, 6 antenna, 7 abdomen, 8 hind leg. Scales 1 mm (Figs 1, 7), 0.5 mm (Figs 6, 8), 0.25 mm (Figs 2 – 5)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/219058/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="496">
Fig. 
<number box="[1216,1229,726,750]" pageId="1" pageNumber="496" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
). Additionally, 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Dexoris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="496" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="chome" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="496">D. chome</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[234,326,761,786]" pageId="1" pageNumber="496" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[234,326,761,786]" pageId="1" pageNumber="496">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
differs in having 
<number box="[536,548,761,786]" pageId="1" pageNumber="496" value="3.0">3</number>
-segmented maxillary palpi (
<number box="[880,894,761,786]" pageId="1" pageNumber="496" value="4.0">4</number>
-segmented in other 
<taxonomicName box="[1134,1223,762,785]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Dexoris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="496" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1134,1223,762,785]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="496">Dexoris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and 
<number box="[1293,1306,761,786]" pageId="1" pageNumber="496" value="2.0">2</number>
-segmented labial palpi (a single free palpomere in other 
<taxonomicName box="[654,743,798,821]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Dexoris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="496" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[654,743,798,821]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="496">Dexoris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species). Male genitalia have a well sclerotized asymmetrical phallobase, unlike other 
<taxonomicName box="[426,515,834,857]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Dexoris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="496" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[426,515,834,857]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="496">Dexoris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[529,661,833,858]" captionStart="FIGURES 9 – 13. 9" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1473,1496]" captionTargetBox="[163,1414,879,1435]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,877,1453]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 9 – 13. 9 Omalisus fontisbellaquaei, general appearance; 10 – 12 Dexoris chome sp. nov., male genitalia; 13 ditto, terminal abdominal segments. Scale 1 mm (Fig. 9), 0.2 mm (Figs 10 – 13)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/219059/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="496">
Figs 
<number box="[586,661,834,858]" pageId="1" pageNumber="496" value="11.0" valueMax="12.0" valueMin="10.0">10–12</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
